---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'AboutPage',
  name: 'About World TV Channels',
  inLanguage: 'en',
};
---
<Base
  title="About — World TV Channels"
  description="What World TV Channels is, why it was built, and how it works."
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article class="legal container">
    <h1>About the project</h1>
    <p class="updated">A small independent project for watching world TV online</p>

    <h2>The idea</h2>
    <p>
      World TV Channels is a free platform that brings together live TV channels
      from around the world in one place. The goal is simple: to help you find a
      channel to watch in seconds — without digging through broadcaster websites,
      without creating accounts, and without a set-top box or satellite dish.
    </p>
    <p>
      It’s designed for anyone curious about global television — from news junkies
      who want to compare how different countries cover the same story, to people
      living abroad who want a taste of home.
    </p>

    <h2>How it’s made</h2>
    <p>
      The project is developed by a small team in their spare time, with no
      outside funding and no affiliation to any particular broadcaster or media
      group. Running costs are covered by unobtrusive advertising banners —
      nothing more.
    </p>
    <p>
      The site you’re using is a static website that plays live streams directly
      in your browser. There’s no app to install — it works in any modern browser
      on desktop and mobile.
    </p>

    <h2>Where the channels come from</h2>
    <p>
      The catalogue is powered entirely by
      <a href="https://github.com/iptv-org/iptv" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">iptv-org</a> —
      an open, community-maintained collection of publicly available TV streams
      from around the world. This keeps the list fresh: when a channel comes
      online or changes its stream, it shows up here without an app update.
    </p>
    <p>
      The content itself — programmes, news, films, advertising — is broadcast by
      the respective channels and belongs entirely to them. World TV Channels
      simply helps you find and play the publicly available streams.
    </p>

    <h2>What we DON’T do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>We don’t store anything about you on a server — we have no user server.</li>
      <li>We don’t require an account, email or phone number.</li>
      <li>We don’t track what you watch — your favorites and history stay in your browser.</li>
      <li>We don’t host or rebroadcast any content — streams come straight from their sources.</li>
      <li>We don’t resell any data.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Technical details</h2>
    <p>
      The web player is a static site built with
      <a href="https://astro.build" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Astro</a> and
      deployed on the edge. Live streams use HLS (HTTP Live Streaming) and are
      played with the open-source
      <a href="https://github.com/video-dev/hls.js" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">hls.js</a>
      library, falling back to native playback on Safari and iOS. Your favorites
      and history are stored locally in your browser (localStorage) and never
      leave your device.
    </p>

    <h2>Blog</h2>
    <p>
      On <a href="/blog">our blog</a> we publish articles about international TV
      channels, broadcasting history and online streaming. If you want to learn
      how IPTV works or discover new channels — take a look.
    </p>

    <h2>Get in touch</h2>
    <p>
      Have feedback, want to report a broken channel, or just say hello? Reach us
      on the <a href="/contact">contact page</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
